# Changelog is mandatory

**Always keep `CHANGELOG.md` up to date.** Any user-facing change (features, fixes, UI copy, behavior changes, removals) needs a bullet under `[Unreleased]` in the same PR/session as the code change. Do not ship or consider work complete without it.

**Keep `ROADMAP.md` in sync when the change affects what users can do today.** Changelog is per-build deltas; the roadmap is the living "what Aware ships" doc (Settings → Roadmap). Update both in the same session when a feature lands, a layer moves from Coming soon to Live now, or existing copy no longer matches the app.

## Format

Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/): `### Added`, `### Changed`, `### Fixed` under `## [Unreleased]`.

Each bullet: **bold headline.** One plain-language sentence of what changed and why it matters to the user. No code refs, file names, view/class names, or implementation detail. Users read this in What's New and Settings → Changelog.

`[Unreleased]` only needs `###` sections and bullets. Bump auto-writes the What's New intro from the bullet headlines if you skip one:

```markdown
## [Unreleased]

### Changed
- **Headline.** What changed.
```

## Voice (write like a human, not a model)

Changelog copy is user-facing. Keep it direct and readable.

- **Short sentences.** Say what changed and why it matters; don't pad with setup clauses or recap the whole subsystem.
- **Plain words.** "Fixed" not "corrected to ensure"; "uses" not "is now wired into".
- **No em dashes (—).** Use commas, periods, or parentheses instead. They read as AI filler when stacked in every bullet.
- **No stacked asides.** One parenthetical or code-ref tail per bullet is enough.
- **Match the project tone.** Casual where it fits ("pile of fixes", "spazzes the camera") is fine; stiff release-notes voice is not.
- **Trim Fixed bullets hardest.** Bug entries tend to balloon into mini post-mortems. State the symptom, the cause in one line if needed, the fix. Done.
- **No implementation detail.** No view names, class names, file paths, or API symbols. Describe what the user sees and does.

Read a bullet aloud. If it sounds like marketing copy or a technical blog post, shorten it.

## Per-build workflow

- **While developing:** add bullets to `## [Unreleased]`
- **Before upload:** hit **Bump** or **Bump + Upload** in ASCManager (or `make bump`). `Tools/BumpRelease.swift` promotes `[Unreleased]` to `## [1.0.0] (B{n}) - YYYY-MM-DD`, auto-writes the What's New intro from bullet headlines, clears `[Unreleased]`, increments `CFBundleVersion`, and bakes `Changelog.generated.swift`
- **After manual edits:** run `make changelog` (or any `make build*`) to rebake `Changelog.generated.swift`
- **After roadmap edits:** run `make roadmap` (or any `make build*`) to rebake `Roadmap.generated.swift`

`(B{n})` must match `CFBundleVersion` in `project.yml`. The in-app **What's New** flow and **Settings → Changelog** both read from `CHANGELOG.md`. **Settings → Roadmap** reads from `ROADMAP.md`.

## When to update

| Change | Section |
|--------|---------|
| New feature or screen | Added |
| Behavior / UX change to existing features | Changed |
| Bug in existing behavior | Fixed |
| Removed or disabled feature | Changed (or Removed if we add that section) |

**Ship new work under Added.** First release of a feature (and its launch polish) belongs in **Added**, not **Changed** or **Fixed**. Don't file "new ISS toggles" under Fixed or "shareable badge cards" under Changed just because you also fixed a bug while building it. Fold launch-time fixes and visual polish into the Added bullet, or add a short Fixed bullet only when it's a distinct bug a user would notice separately.

**Fixed is for regressions and broken existing behavior.** Bugs found while building a brand-new feature are part of that feature's Added entry unless they're clearly unrelated.

Skip changelog only for pure refactors, comments, or tooling with zero user impact.

**Skip changelog for copy/voice polish.** Tweaks that only fix stiff or AI-sounding wording (em dashes, "in your location", marketing filler) do not get a bullet. The user already gets the better text; a changelog entry that says you removed an em dash or de-AI'd a string is its own tell. If the copy change ships with a real feature or fix, fold it into that bullet or stay silent.

## Roadmap (`ROADMAP.md`)

Same voice as changelog: plain language, what the user gets, no file names or implementation detail. Tables and `###` subsections parse into the in-app timeline; keep that structure.

### When to update

| Change | Roadmap |
|--------|---------|
| New feature, screen, layer, or alert type users can use | Yes. Add under the right section; move Coming soon → Live now when it ships. |
| UX that changes what a feature does or where it lives | Yes if the "what you get" table or bullets would mislead without an edit. |
| Bug fix or visual polish on something already documented | Usually no. Changelog only. |
| Dev-only surfaces (Next build teaser, banner preview) | No. |
| Removed or held-back feature | Yes. Drop from Live now or move back to Coming soon; refresh **Summary**. |

### Checklist

- New capability: bullet or table row in the matching section (Map, Safety, Contacts, etc.).
- Shipped layer: remove from **Coming soon**, add to **Live now**.
- **Summary** at the bottom still matches the headline list of what Aware ships today.
- Run `make roadmap` after editing (same habit as `make changelog`).
